## Platform Safari:
> May 6, 
 1. Desktop:
Steam
 Steam runs as a full desktop application installed on Windows, which gives it direct access to powerful hardware like dedicated GPUs, large storage, and high performance CPUs. Because of this, it can run and manage large, graphics intensive games that would be impossible to play in a browser or on mobile. The desktop platform also allows features like mod support, local file access, and high speed downloads through the OS’s networking stack. The limitation, though, is that Steam is tied to a stationary device. I can’t easily play or manage my library on the go the way I could with a mobile app, and installing games requires significant disk space and system resources that lighter platforms don’t demand.
 2. IOS mobile app on an iPhone:
Spotify
 A mobile app on iOS or Android for streaming music seamlessly while on the move, switch audio output instantly to Bluetooth headphones or my car, and respond to hardware buttons on the phone for quick play/pause without opening the app. Those interactions would be hard to implement if not impossible on a desktop browser. One drawback is that you cannot freely access the files or move them into a different folder the way you would on a desktop app, because IOS restricts direct file access.
 3. Web app in a browser:
Google Docs
 Google Docs on the web excels because the browser is made for real-time collaboration. Multiple people can edit the same document simultaneously, and the platform handles the syncing, history, and any conflict resolution without any installation. Collaboration is harder on a desktop-only-app with some people always having limited accessibility to their desktop. The draw back for Google Docs though is that is depends on internet connection, take for example, if my internet connection were to drop all of a sudden, the features like live collaborations or even saving the changes become unreliable. This drawback does not apply to a native desktop word processor that does not use internet wouldn’t suffer from.


